objectType.description: The level of the IBM IPSec MIB.

The objects defined in this table are used to for the
management of IKE (Phase-1) Tunnel. There is one
entry in this table for each Phase-1 Tunnel.

Each entry contains attributes associated with a
Phase-1 IKE tunnel.

The index of the Phase-1 Tunnel table.
The value of the index is a number which begins at one and
is incremented with each tunnel that is created. The value
of this object will wrap at 65535.
The internal ID of the Phase-1 Tunnel.
The local IP Address the Phase-1 Tunnel.
The local name of the Phase-1 Tunnel.
The local IP Address the Phase-1 Tunnel.
The remote name of the Phase-1 Tunnel.
The negotiation mode of the Phase-1 Tunnel.
The lifetime of the Phase-1 Tunnel in seconds.

The length of time the tunnel has been active in
hundredths of seconds.

The security association refresh threshold percentage
of the Phase-1 Tunnel.
The total number of security associations refreshes completed.
The total number of octets received by this Phase-1 Tunnel.
The total number of packets received by this Phase-1 Tunnel.

The total number of packets dropped by this Phase-1 Tunnel
during receive processing.
The total number of notifications received by this Phase-1 Tunnel.
The total number of proposals received by this Phase-1 Tunnel.

The total number of proposals received by this Phase-1 Tunnel
which were invalid.

The total number of proposals received by this Phase-1 Tunnel
which were rejected.

The total number of security association deleted requests
received by this Phase-1 Tunnel.
The total number of octets sent by this Phase-1 Tunnel.
The total number of packets sent by this Phase-1 Tunnel.

The total number of packets dropped by this Phase-1 Tunnel
during send processing.
The total number of notifications sent by this Phase-1 Tunnel.
The total number of Phase-2 Proposals sent by this Phase-1 Tunnel.

The total number of Phase-2 Proposals sent by this Phase-1 Tunnel
which were rejected.

The total number of security association deleted requests
sent by this Phase-1 Tunnel.

The status of the MIB table row. This object
can be used to bring the tunnel down by setting
value of this object to destroy(2).
This object cannot be used to create a MIB table row.
The total number of currently active IPSec Phase-2 Tunnels.
The total number of previously active IPSec Phase-2 Tunnels.

The total number of octets received by all current and previous
IPSec Phase-2 Tunnels. See also ipSecGlobalInOctWraps for

The total number of packets received by all current and previous
IPSec Phase-2 Tunnels.

The total number of packets dropped during receive processing

The total number of inbound authentication's performed

The total number of inbound authentication's which ended in failure

The total number of inbound decryption's performed
by all current and previous IPSec Phase-2 Tunnels.

The total number of inbound decryption's which ended in failure
by all current and previous IPSec Phase-2 Tunnels.

The total number of octets sent by all current and previous
IPSec Phase-2 Tunnels. See also ipSecGlobalOutOctWraps for
the number of times this counter has wrapped.

The total number of packets sent by all current and previous
IPSec Phase-2 Tunnels.

The total number of packets dropped during send processing

The total number of outbound authentication's performed

The total number of outbound authentication's which ended in failure

The total number of outbound encryption's performed
by all current and previous IPSec Phase-2 Tunnels.

The total number of outbound encryption's which ended in failure

The number of times the total number of octets received counter
(ipSecGlobalInOctets) has wrapped.

The number of times the total number of octets sent counter
(ipSecGlobalOutOctets) has wrapped.
The IPSec Phase-2 Tunnel table.
An IPSec Phase-2 Tunnel entry.

The index of the Phase-2 Tunnel table.
The value of the index is a number which begins at one and
is incremented with each tunnel that is created. The value
of this object will wrap at 65535.
The internal ID of the Phase-2 Tunnel.
The index of the related IKE Phase-1 Tunnel. (ikeTunnelIndex)
The local IP address of the Phase-2 Tunnel.
The remote IP address of the Phase-2 Tunnel.
The type of key used by the Phase-2 Tunnel.
The encapsulation mode used by the Phase-2 Tunnel.
The defined lifetime of the tunnel in hundredths of seconds.

The length of time the tunnel has been active in
hundredths of seconds.

The security association refresh threshold percentage
of the tunnel.
The number of security association refreshes performed.
The number of security association which have expired.

The number of security associations which are currently
active or expiring.
The encryption used by the inbound security association.

The authentication algorithm used by the inbound
security association.
The encryption used by the outbound security association.

The authentication algorithm used by the outbound

The number of octets received. This value is accumulated
BEFORE determining whether or not the packet should be
decompressed. See also ipSecTunnelInOctWraps for the
number of times this counter has wrapped.

The number of decompressed octets received. This value is
accumulated AFTER the packet is decompressed. If compression
is not being used, this value will match the value of
ipSecTunnelInOctets. See also ipSecTunnelInDecompOctWraps for
the number of times this counter has wrapped.
The number of packets received.
The number of packets dropped during received processing.
The total number of inbound authentication's performed.

accumulated BEFORE the packet is compress. If compression

ipSecTunnelOutOctets. See also ipSecTunnelOutUncompOctWraps
for the number of times this counter has wrapped.
The number of packets sent.
The number of packets dropped during send processing.
The total number of outbound authentication's performed.
The number of outbound authentication's which failed.
The total number of outbound encryption's performed.
The number of outbound encryption's which failed.

The status of the MIB table row. This object
can be used to:
1) allow user-data traffic flow through this tunnel
by setting this the value of this object to
active (1).
2 bring the tunnel down by setting the value
of this object to destroy(2).
3) stop all user-data traffic flow through the tunnel by
setting the value of this object to disable(3).
This object cannot be used to create a MIB table row.

Valid Status Changes

New Status
+---------+---------+---------+
Current Status | active | destroy | disable |
+---------------+=========+=========+=========+
| active | Valid | Valid | Valid |
+---------------+---------+---------+---------+
| destroy | Invalid | Invalid | Invalid |
+---------------+---------+---------+---------+
| disable | Valid | Valid | Valid |
+---------------+---------+---------+---------+

The IPSec Phase-2 Tunnel Client table.
An IPSec Phase-2 Tunnel Client entry.

The number of the Client associated with the Phase-2 Tunnel table.
The value of this number begins at one and is incremented
with each Client associated with a Phase-2 Tunnel. For example,
each Phase-2 Tunnel may have Client Indices of 1 through 65,535.
The value of this object will wrap at 65535.
The local name of the Client.

The local entry type. Possible values are:
1) The local IP Address Range is being used, or
2) The local IP Subnet Mask is being used.
The local protocol number for this Client.
The local subnet mask of the Client.
The local high IP Address of the Client.
The local low IP Address of the Client.
The local port of the Client.
The remote name of the Client.

The remote entry type. Possible values are:
1) The remote IP Address Range is being used, or
2) The remote IP Subnet Mask is being used.
The remote protocol number for this Client.
The remote subnet mask of the Client.
The remote high IP Address of the Client.
The remote low IP Address of the Client.
The remote port of the Client.
The IPSec Phase-2 Security Protection Index table.
An IPSec Phase-2 Security Protection Index entry.

The number of the SPI associated with the Phase-2 Tunnel table.
The value of this number begins at one and is incremented
with each SPI associated with a Phase-2 Tunnel. For example,
each Phase-2 Tunnel may have Client Indices of 1 through 65,535.
The value of this object will wrap at 65535.
The direction of the SPI.
The value of the SPI.
The protocol of the SPI.
The status of the SPI.

The length of time the tunnel was active in hundredths of seconds.

An IPSec Phase-2 Failure entry.
